caption: Fantastic sushi and other Japanese small plates experience. I had 4 various small plates, the 10 piece sushi omakase, and the seared belly trio. All of the dishes were exquisite. The monkfish karaage was a particular highlight out of the small plates. The sushi choices were also outstanding, with some interesting garnishes and touches on the more delicate fishes to up the flavor complexity.  The service is extremely helpful and friendly, and the food came relatively quickly. The ambiance was also very nice and all staff were properly masked. Easy 5/5 for me and would definitely visit again.

This place doesn't get enough love for how good it is. A bit further away from Cobble Hill than the spots on Smith, but far superior. It's tucked away on a pretty nothing block. When you can eat indoors, very intimate.
The food was good but I think the workers are not really nice.

Updated 12/5/20: Taiki continues to be a standout in the neighborhood. Exceptional sushi and service, for takeout, delivery and dine-in. Their takeout/delivery is very thoughtfully and beautifully packaged, with each of the fish identified in the sushi/sashimi dinner. I appreciate that they have the usual and unexpected kinds of fish. Please support this neighborhood gem!  Original review: Delicious sushi and appetizers, and a very beautiful and chill vibe
Amazing food. Amazing staff. This is a great place for date night. Covid precautions honored. Indoor and outdoor seating available. Support small businesses.

Love Taiki. Great neighborhood OR destination spot. Nice outdoor seating for COVID, takeout menu too, and really fresh fish. Some of the best sushi we've had in 8+ years in NYC. Staff is really nice too. Go support them!

If you're into miniature doll houses and figurines. Then Taiki Restaurant is the place for you, average tasting miniature cocktail size Sushi at the price of regular size Sushi.  "Tiny Taiki Sushi Bites"  "Overpriced tiny size"  "Tic Tac Sushi"  "Great service, outrageous price"
The place offers an awesome variety of delicious food. I love dining here. Employees are always nice, rates are convenient and the spot is always clean.
Truly special sushi with excellent service. The bluefin tuna tasting is outstanding, especially the fatty otoro. Love that I can get this high end stuff delivered too!
Amazing food

0 stars for fish quality and customer service. I was upset about receiving stringy, smelly, and practically inedible tuna and chutoro (which is not cheap). I called to politely complain and get a refund for those few items. The owner, Taiki, proceeded to argue with me and say that my complaints are untrue and impossible. After going back and forth for a few minutes he said he would update the charge, which never happened. $35 for four small pieces of fish down the toilet.

One of the best sushi experiences in the city. Not sure what the previous reviewer was thinking by ordering takeout, must be trippin’ to pull that move on high quality Japanese. They have outdoor seating and make sure you do the omakase.

Ordered their takeout omokase and wow, it was garbage. The fish tasted like it came out of a freezer, the rice was dry, and the textures were all around unpleasant. I am extremely disappointed because I usually enjoy fresh sushi, but this restaurant was just a complete letdown. One star is honestly too generous. Do yourself a favor and avoid eating here.
Some of the best sushi in Brooklyn. Now doing takeout and delivery! Highly recommend both in and out of Quarantine.
Love the place. Cozy.
Amazing sushi and service! Cute for date night as it feels very private and nice in there.
Friendly, great music, relaxed, amazing sushi, worth the price. Wonderful date night!

This site is my favorite restaurant.  Of all restaurants I know I like it most. I never miss an opportunity to go to this restaurant. when  I feel like having a special lunchon, this place comes straight to my mind. outstanding and all sorts of  food and a large list of dishes.professional staff, and agreeable vibes. And very important, the tariff is good. I praise this restaurant with no hesitation.
Came here for Restaurant Week and everything was perfectly delicious. Service was impeccable, and ambiance was great. Would totally return and recommend!
2020.01 restaurant week. To me.   Portion a bit small.  8 pieces sushi.   Taste good, but can be better.  Fresh fish.  Very tender.  Chair is a little not comfy.  Small size Abt 20 seats.
The best sushi in Brooklyn and top 5 in NYC.  Sit at the bar, order the Omakase and bottle of sake.

Food was fantastic, sushi very fresh. Unfortunately everything is super overpriced! We got 3 rolls, 2 app and beers over for over $100!! Way too expensive. The staff was very friendly but didn't have enough help, we went Saturday night and there were 2 waiters and only one sushi chef. This place is not managed efficiently.
Omg the service here is incredible! And the sushi is out of this world! Happy hour specials are legit - come at 6 for well prices chef special sushi and saki
Excellent fresh fish. Small but cozy establishment. Service was superb.
Great place wonderful go- to if you're in mood for sushi highly recommend
Exceptional service in a small lovely friendly restaurant. Amazing sushi and sashimi. Not the usual fare.

Great food and service! A subtle and cozy spot, it has great dishes that are well thought-out and executed. I took off a star because despite spending $50 per person, I felt hungry afterwards. I recommend the monkfish Karaage, the eggplant and shishito small dish and the edamame!

We had an amazing dinner at Taiki. I’m still daydreaming about the tasty cabbage appetizer. Our sushi was incredible and super fresh, and my sake yuzu mojito was perfectly refreshing. We had a delicious dessert (I forget the name of it, sorry) that served perfect proportions of crunchy sweet and tart flavors. We will absolutely visit Taiki again.

On a lark I walked in for happy hour omakase and got seated right at the bar. The chef was busy and efficient but still made plenty of time to talk about sushi, fish, food, NYC over the years, and even knives.  After my omakase I decided to grab a few extra pieces of sushi - I was advised to try the Japanese barracuda and another species which I cannot recall. Both were excellent, and the chef skillfully prepared and even lightly charred the exterior before serving it.  At the end of the meal I thanked the chef and excused myself, only to find out that he was Taiki himself! I had a great meal, great service and fantastic company - I highly recommend that you stop in.

Saw the New York restaurant week promo outside the restaurant and decided to try it out. Went in 15 mins before HH is over and took advantage of it. Had the chamosan and a sale mojito (can’t recall the exact name) and they were light and refreshing for such a humid and muggy day. The monkfish karaage & crab cakes appetizer are on point. Lightly battered and done so well and the dip for the crab cakes went so well with the monkfish too. The chef Sushi selection is well spread out. I’m not good with sour taste so the yuzu sorbet is a pass though I did try a few spoonfuls. Overall, a great dinner and music is jamming!
Appetizers were amazing and nice place, but underwhelmed by the sushi rolls and crazy overpriced for the neighborhood.

We went there because it was down the block from where we were staying. The restaurant is small, and because we were a bigger group (6), we were placed in a dark corner in the back. It felt a bit stuffy. Service was exceptionally slow. The 12-piece omakase didn’t really fill me up. Thank goodness for the leftover rolls the kids did not finish. It was really just okay.

Sushi was overall tasty, but found the service a little slow.  Ate the 12 piece omakase at a table (not the sushi bar).  At $60 for 12 pieces, did not seem too expensive.  Happy hour seemed like a better deal, but wasn't going to be enough food!
!Great Omakase in Brooklyn!
Definitely one of the top sushi places in Brooklyn. The small plates and desert are fantastic.
Great sushi!

Great vibe. Menu is thought out. It's a bit pricey for the actual food portions/quality. I would come again but if the price would meet it's quality, I would have rated it a 5. Otherwise, it's a nice place to visit once in a while. Not your sushi to go place, unfortunately.

Seems like this place caters to the gentrified palate of the hood. While that's great, if someone asks for siracha in a Japanese restaurant, it's expected that they should have, if not siracha, then some other type of hot sauce. Hot beverages were served in cups that got too hot to hold; insulated cups would be better to avoid discomfort.  The food itself was very good, with an excellent blend of classic authentic Japanese cuisine and modern flair. A bit pricey considering Google's rating indicated $$, more like $$$. The service was fast, friendly and efficient. I would recommend trying it for yourself.

I visit Japan pretty often and always look for Omakase experiences in the city when I can.. I walked in and asked for a bar seat with no reservations thankfully they sat me in front of Chef taiki! I did the Omakase cause I love watching the chefs do their work while I just look at how cool it is. Happily paid a bit less than 100 dollars for what I ordered tuna tasting, Omakase and some extras at the end.. I need to come back!  Updated on 2/17/19 Brought the girlfriend here for late valentine's day. I'm happy to see the space so busy even at 6o clock. I walked in with no reservation and still was able to see on the bar. It was super busy but food and service quality didn't suffer I love their cocktails the lemonade sake! Sorry forgot to take a picture of the cocktails
The fish was very fresh and the highlight for me. The sashimi platter plain and well prepared. The service was very friendly when I visited on what looked like a slow evening.

We were here last weekend on a whim I wanted sushi...and this place was amazing! Our server recommended a dish and it was delicious! I'm from Delaware but next time I'm in town I will have to stop back in!
Hidden gem
Great quality and fresh fish
What an amazing experience. The sushi was amazing and our serving was knowledgeable. Everything he suggested  was spot on. I will def be back

Fish quality and variations are good, definitely one of the top choices in Brooklyn. Staff is very attentive and friendly. I wish I could love it but the platter omakase approach plus the flashy vibe made it less appealing.

Easily worst meal we’ve had in the city. We knew it was going to be a disappointment as soon as we sat in their uncomfortable bar stool seating. After spending $130 plus tip on sushi —that tasted like fish flavored rice—we rushed over to the bodega across the street to grab chips and ice cream, thinking about how we could’ve gotten better delivery. I don’t know what other people are raving about. The chopsticks were nice. I don’t know what we were thinking going to a Japanese restaurant in a residential area with low turnover. I wish we never sat down.

The sushi is great! It's clear they get their sushi on the day it's served no two to the three day sushi here. The specials are not gimmicks they vary and are always delightful. They have have a great children's menu on Friday worth checking out. Don't go there expecting outstanding service though. This is a whole in the wall joint that aims to serve great food. That said the staff is good and chef is outstanding.
I’ve been to Sushi joints all over Japan. This place is fantastic!
It's hard to believe such great sushi is right around the corner.  The omokase was excellent, and the service matched.  Highly recommended.

strange precut thin pieces of fish quickly assembled to make sushi...  omakase made as a platter, nothing prepared "fresh" from chef standing in front of you at sushi bar.  they did have a nice seasonal selection and fish tasted good.
Really good food but expensive

Lovely restaurant with delicious sushi. Service can be slow if it's busy as there is only one sushi chef but it's worth the wait. They have an unbelievable deal on the kid's menu and are reasonably kid-friendly (although they do not have high chairs).

On one hand, the food was very good - excellent, full flavor sushi that's, as another reviewer mentioned, gotta be right up there with the best places in Brooklyn. Nice soup too. On the other: surprisingly pricey for the neighborhood and what you get. I mean, omakase sounded like a really good deal when I thought it involved the chef offering up one piece at a time and all - but it wasn't that, it was a very good "sushi platter" assembled and handed over with a quick rundown of what each fish was. For a completely ala carte sushi platter - I ordered the gazpacho separately when informed that nothing else comes with the omakase - well, it's a less appealing proposition for the price. Very different experience: you're not getting each piece the moment it's made, nor the interaction with the chef, nor the pacing which arises from that experience. Eating alone that evening, I found myself finished very quickly, even though I slowed down to savor each bite and paused between them, reflecting and cleaning my palate with ginger and sips of wine.  So instead of the omakase bargain I hoped for ("ah, it's a discount for being on unglamorous Nevins St in the shadow of the projects") it was a lot to spend on a quick (and good, definitely) sushi dinner which had me in and out pretty fast.
Delicious. Not quite as good as top sushi in the city but one of the best sushis in bkln.
Very friendly staff and sexy ambiance. Great for date night.
Solid Sushi with alot of options and an intimate dining atmosphere.
Very good resturant love the sushi best sushi ever😙😙😙😚😚😚😗😗😘🤣😂😂😉
Just delicious! Awesome food and great service. We will be coming back and repeat !!!

This immediately became one of our favorite restaurants, and about the only Sushi place my wife loves. We go for birthdays and bring friends from Manhattan and out of towners to have some of the best fish in the city. Friendly owner and staff as well!

The environment is dark and cozy. It is a good place to hang out with a good friend or as a date, not a good place for big parties. Good food in really SMALL portions. The food has a lot of spices and has a really STRONG, particular taste. Taiki has a new take on Japanese food. It is not kid friendly.  P.S. The edamame is AMAZING!!!!! 😉😊
Incredible. Don't tell anyone. Best secret.
Fantastic local gem. Sat with the chef by the same name and ate our way thru the menu. Sushi was fresh and delicious. Jonathan was our server and made the night perfect.

This is a nice addition to the neighborhood. The place is very relaxed compared to most of the Japanese places in the area.  The food was good. They are creating dishes that are more creative than other spots around here as well like toro tartare with crispy rice, gazpacho, miso soup in chowder form with bacon. We enjoyed the yellowtail salad, the fried monkfish and the sushi too.

This is the best sushi I have ever had in Sushi. Anyone that likes bondst in the city needs to eat here because the sushi is 10x better. Omakase and all rolls are a necessity, you must try this place. Abeline is the culinary curator at the restaurant.

Amazing local spot with top top top quality sushi. They have ruined us for any of the other local sushi haunts. Chef Taiki is very talented and fun to chat with. The fish is incredibly fresh and the appetizers are unique and inventive. Don't miss the shishito mussels and miso chowder.

This place was absolutely amazing. My wife and I went there at 10:30 for a light meal. We immediately sat at the bar and were greeting quickly by the waiter. He provided cucumber water and gave a nice description of what he had to drink. Our drinks came out fairly quickly and in nice glasses. We then got to order our meal from master chef Taiki himself. We ordered miso, a tuna roll, and 10 pieces of nigiri. The miso came out quickly and was perfect temperature to eat immediately. He then prepared our tuna roll in front of us and laid it on a big leaf as a driving plate (maybe a rubber tree leave?) After we finished the roll he then made piece by piece and laid it in front of us. I don't even know how to describe how delicious it tastes as I probably won't do it justice. After the nigiri he made us a small Japanese cake dish on the house, wiped his knife clean, and thanked us. The ambience was amazing, great lighting with very cool tunes going on. The price was a little high but it's absolutely worth it. I cannot recommend this place enough but can only a few of you guys come to help his business but not enough so I don't have to wait to eat there?

Small japanese spot in downtown brooklyn.  Omakase meal is more like a sushi deluxe setting.  All nigiri is provided all at once.  Food quality is fine, but nothing really stood out except for the ikura.  Service was good.  Its a descent local spot, but there are better available if you are willing to travel

Upon our arrival, the staff was extremely warm and welcoming. I am Japanese, so coming from Japan and trying out sushi spots in NYC, my experience is typically disappointing. However, my experience here has been outstanding and has given me a more positive outlook and eating a staple Japanese food. The wait for food was not long at all, considering what we got, however much time spent on it probably wouldn't matter (it was that good)! The texture of the fresh fish was exquisite. I would highly recommend the mussel shishito as a starter, the "Omakase" (this means the "chefs pick") sushi, the Blue Fish Tuna tasting (which consists of 5 different types of textured/tasting tuna), the ika (squid) sushi was one of my daughters favorite, and the tamago brûlée dessert was the ultimate way to put a halt to our ovehelming sushi feast!  Additionally, considering its location... it's truly a hidden gem!
The best server I've ever had!
Amazing high end sushi. Simple but perfectly done.
Wonderful new addition to the neighborhood. Taiki's passion and attention to detail results in the best quality sushi!
